In Week 3 of Trump\'92s second term, the pattern that had been forming snapped into clearer view. Power no longer flowed only through the visible levers of office. It moved along private channels, through a new, informal ministry run by a single billionaire, and it moved through fear, as purges and threats reached deep into the civil service and law enforcement. The week\'92s events did not yet close the space for opposition, but they changed the cost of using it. They also changed who, in practice, could see and touch the machinery of the state. The Democracy Clock, which had stood at 7:34 p.m., advanced to 7:35 p.m. The half\uc0\u8209 minute shift was small, but it marked a week when several guardrails were pierced at once and when the line between public office and private power grew thinner and harder to see.\
\
The previous week had left the clock at 7:34 p.m., with institutions strained but still recognizably within the frame of a constitutional republic. By the close of Week 3, the time was 7:35 p.m., a net move of half a minute toward midnight. The change came not from a single spectacular act, but from a cluster of structural moves. Inspectors general were removed from at least a dozen agencies. The Justice Department and FBI were purged of people tied to investigations of Trump and January 6. Elon Musk\'92s \'93Department of Government Efficiency\'94 gained access to federal payment systems and personnel databases that touch nearly every household and every civil servant in the country. At the same time, courts, unions, and some state governments fought back, blocking a freeze on federal funds, halting a coercive buyout of federal workers, and stopping an attempt to end birthright citizenship. The clock moved because the balance between these forces shifted. Executive power and its private partners gained new reach, while the institutions meant to watch and restrain them were weakened or forced into emergency posture.\
\
The most striking development of the week was the fusion of state power with a private operation centered on Elon Musk. Treasury Secretary Scott Bessent granted Musk\'92s team access to the federal payment systems that move roughly six trillion dollars a year in Social Security checks, Medicare reimbursements, tax refunds, and grants. Reporting and lawsuits showed that this access was not confined to harmless observation. DOGE operatives could see coded payment data and, in some accounts, cancel transactions they deemed wasteful, including a free online tax filing system. At the Office of Personnel Management, Musk\'92s associates installed a new server in a conference room, outside normal procurement channels and without a required privacy assessment. They gained broad access to databases holding medical histories, Social Security numbers, and performance records for millions of federal employees, while senior civil servants were locked out of the same systems. Similar incursions took place at the Small Business Administration, the Department of Education, NOAA, the Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services, and the Department of Energy. In each case, the pattern was the same. A private team, loyal to the president but not answerable to Congress or the public, was allowed to reach into the core systems that make the state function.\
\
This shift in control over information and payments did not occur in a vacuum. It was paired with a campaign to thin out and intimidate the professional civil service that might have resisted it. OPM, under Musk\'92s influence, emailed all federal employees with an offer of \'93deferred resignation\'94: full pay and benefits until the end of September for those who agreed to quit. The fine print told a different story. Agencies could require employees to keep working, could refuse to rescind resignations, and workers waived their right to enforce the agreement in court. Around 20,000 accepted before a federal judge stepped in to pause the program\'92s deadline and call for a hearing on its legality. At the State Department, a hiring freeze led to the abrupt termination of personal services contractors who provided security and support at embassies. At USAID, two top security officials were placed on leave after they tried to block DOGE\'92s access to classified systems. The message was clear. Those who insisted on rules and clearances risked their jobs, while those who cooperated with the new order advanced.\
\
Oversight inside agencies was also stripped away. Trump removed inspectors general from at least twelve major departments, eliminating internal watchdogs whose job is to audit spending, investigate misconduct, and report to Congress. At the same time, a Wired investigation revealed that a young engineer with ties to Musk\'92s companies had direct access to Treasury systems that could, in theory, alter payments. The combination was stark. As private actors gained unprecedented reach into the state\'92s financial and personnel arteries, the officials designed to monitor such risks were dismissed. This was not a symbolic change. It altered the daily incentives of thousands of managers and contractors, who now had fewer reasons to fear internal scrutiny and more reasons to align with political directives. It also made any later effort to rebuild routine oversight slower and harder.\
\
The Justice Department and the FBI were reshaped in parallel. Acting Deputy Attorney General Emil Bove ordered the firing of roughly two dozen prosecutors who had worked on January 6 cases and other prosecutions involving Trump. Acting Attorney General James McHenry carried out Trump\'92s personal instructions to dismiss more than a dozen special counsel prosecutors. At the FBI, at least nine high\uc0\u8209 ranking officials were forced out, and the bureau was told to compile lists of agents who had worked on the Capitol riot and Trump investigations. Thousands of employees received detailed questionnaires about their roles. The FBI complied in part, sending the Justice Department a list of employee numbers and job titles. Two groups of agents sued to block the release of names, arguing that the lists would be used for retaliation. A senior FBI official in New York wrote to staff describing a climate of fear. In the same week, Attorney General Pam Bondi disbanded the FBI\'92s Foreign Influence Task Force and dismantled the Justice Department\'92s foreign bribery and kleptocracy units, while scaling back white\u8209 collar enforcement. The law was being redirected: away from corruption and foreign interference, and toward culture\u8209 war targets and immigration.\
\
These moves were framed and justified through a new narrative about \'93weaponization.\'94 Trump signed an executive order directing the attorney general to produce a report on the supposed weaponization of the federal government, explicitly including the special counsel cases against him. Bondi launched a \'93Weaponization Working Group\'94 to review prosecutions of Trump and January 6 defendants. In this telling, prior efforts to hold the president and his allies accountable became abuses to be exposed and reversed. The same week, Trump issued blanket pardons for more than 1,500 January 6 participants, even as some, like Andrew Taake, were arrested on unrelated charges such as soliciting a minor. The combined effect was to recast the insurrection as a wrong done to loyal supporters rather than an attack on the peaceful transfer of power, and to signal that loyalty to the president could outweigh the law. It also sent a warning to future prosecutors and agents about the personal risks of pursuing cases that touch the ruling circle.\
\
While law enforcement was bent inward, the presidency reached outward through emergency powers and foreign policy. On February 1, Trump invoked national emergency authorities to impose sweeping tariffs on imports from Canada, Mexico, and China, citing drug trafficking and illegal immigration. The tariffs were broad\'9725 percent on most goods from Canada and Mexico, 10 percent on Chinese products\'97and they broke existing trade agreements. Markets fell, and allies protested. Canada, Mexico, and China announced retaliatory tariffs and WTO complaints. Within days, after hurried negotiations and symbolic concessions on border enforcement, Trump paused the tariffs on Canada and Mexico for a month, but left the threat hanging. The Postal Service briefly halted parcels from China and Hong Kong, likely tied to changes in duty\uc0\u8209 free rules, before reversing course. The pattern was one of shakedown diplomacy: use economic shock to extract concessions, then declare victory.\
\
Foreign aid and multilateral engagement were treated in the same transactional spirit. Trump froze roughly $60 billion in USAID funding for a 90\uc0\u8209 day review and moved to fold the agency into the State Department, with Secretary of State Marco Rubio declaring himself acting USAID administrator. USAID\'92s headquarters was closed, its website and social media accounts went dark, and plaques were removed from its building. Musk called the agency a \'93criminal organization\'94 and boasted that his team was shutting down federal grants. Emails later showed that the freeze was not a mere technical review of payment systems, as the administration claimed, but a deliberate halt to humanitarian programs in places like Gaza, Sudan, and Ukraine. Labor unions representing USAID staff sued Trump, Rubio, and Bessent, arguing that dismantling the agency without congressional approval was unconstitutional and illegal. The administration also withdrew the United States from the UN Human Rights Council and cut funding to UNRWA, the main agency serving Palestinian refugees, while ordering a review of all support to international organizations.\
