At home, the administration used executive orders to reorder social hierarchies and civil rights. Trump revoked a 60\uc0\u8209 year\u8209 old order that barred employment discrimination by federal contractors, and he directed agencies to treat many diversity, equity, and inclusion programs as illegal discrimination against white men. Federal employees were told to strip pronouns from email signatures. West Point disbanded twelve student\u8209 led clubs, including groups for women engineers, Latin culture, and LGBTQ cadets. The State Department suspended a Christian employee group that had promoted religious diversity. An order on antisemitism directed agencies to identify civil and criminal tools to use against campus protests, with a fact sheet suggesting deportation of international students who joined pro\u8209 Palestinian demonstrations. Another order banned gender\u8209 affirming care for people under nineteen at hospitals receiving federal funds, leading major institutions to suspend such services. A separate directive purged transgender service members from the military, ordered trans prisoners to be medically \'93detransitioned\'94 and moved to facilities matching their sex at birth, and barred trans women and girls from competing in female sports, with visa denials for trans athletes seeking to enter the United States. Federal judges in Washington and elsewhere stepped in to block the prison transfers and some aspects of the birthright citizenship and asylum orders, but the thrust of policy was clear. The state would now use its power to enforce a narrow vision of gender, sexuality, and belonging.\
