Religion was drawn more tightly into this project. Trump signed an order establishing a White House Faith Office to coordinate with faith\uc0\u8209 based groups and ensure they could compete for federal funding. Another order created a task force to \'93eradicate anti\u8209 Christian bias\'94 in the federal government, chaired by the attorney general and including representatives from multiple agencies. These moves were framed as protecting religious liberty, but in practice they elevated one religious identity as especially deserving of state protection and attention. Combined with the antisemitism order\'92s focus on campus protest and the withdrawal from UN human rights bodies, they signaled a reorientation of rights discourse: away from universal protections and toward the defense of favored constituencies. They also gave the administration new tools to mobilize supporters and to cast critics as hostile to faith itself.\
