Against this backdrop, courts and civil society mounted a series of defensive actions. Federal judges in Washington and Seattle blocked Trump\'92s attempt to freeze grants and loans, citing a 1974 law that bars presidents from impounding funds appropriated by Congress. Another judge extended a pause on the administration\'92s funding freeze, warning of catastrophic impacts. Courts in multiple jurisdictions enjoined the birthright citizenship order, with one Reagan\uc0\u8209 appointed judge calling it \'93clearly unconstitutional.\'94 A district judge halted the federal employee buyout deadline, giving unions time to argue that the program was coercive and unlawful. The ACLU sued over an executive order that effectively suspended asylum law. Federal employee unions and three major unions representing civil servants filed suit to stop DOGE\'92s access to Treasury payment systems and to protect privacy rights. Two anonymous OPM employees went to court to shut down the servers Musk\'92s team had installed. Labor unions sued to reverse USAID cuts and the foreign aid freeze. In North Carolina, a judge found racial bias in a death row sentencing, and a class action was filed against a prison gynecologist accused of years of abuse. These cases did not reverse the week\'92s structural changes, but they showed that the judiciary and organized labor remained willing to confront executive overreach.\
