Public protest filled some of the space left by institutional constraint. Thousands gathered near the Capitol to denounce Musk\'92s access to taxpayer data and Trump\'92s broader agenda, joined by more than two dozen Democratic members of Congress. Crowds assembled outside the Treasury Department to object to DOGE\'92s control over payment systems. In North Carolina, activists organized demonstrations at Senator Thom Tillis\'92s office to oppose cabinet nominees like Russell Vought. Across the country, calls to Senate offices surged as news of Musk\'92s role and the Gaza proposal spread. Even some groups that had once supported Trump shifted. \'93Arab Americans for Trump\'94 rebranded as \'93Arab Americans for Peace\'94 after the Gaza announcement, signaling a break over foreign policy. These actions did not stop the week\'92s executive orders, but they showed that the moral floor of public life had not yet collapsed, even as it cracked.\
\
Looking ahead from the vantage of Week 3, several decisions already in motion promised to test the system further. The Supreme Court\'92s consideration of the nondelegation doctrine threatened to reshape the balance between Congress and regulatory agencies. The lawsuits over DOGE\'92s access to federal databases and payment systems, and over USAID\'92s dismantling, would determine whether private actors could remain embedded in the state\'92s core functions. The Gaza plan, sanctions on the International Criminal Court, and the withdrawal from UN human rights bodies set the stage for sustained conflict with international law. The reinstatement of the federal death penalty, the expansion of migrant detention at Guantanamo, and the dismantling of foreign influence and anti\uc0\u8209 kleptocracy units raised questions about how elections would be protected from foreign money and disinformation. Each of these threads was already on the docket of courts, legislatures, or international bodies. None required speculation. They were simply the next steps in a path already chosen.\
\
By the end of the week, the Democracy Clock\'92s move to 7:35 p.m. captured a simple fact. The formal architecture of American democracy still stood: courts issued injunctions, Congress held hearings and passed bills, states asserted their own laws, and citizens protested in the streets. But the internal wiring of that architecture was being rerouted. Executive power was exercised with less restraint and more reliance on emergency claims. Law was used more often as a shield for allies and a sword against opponents than as a neutral limit. Appointments and access were granted on the basis of loyalty and wealth rather than competence. Oversight bodies, from inspectors general to the FEC, were fired, sidelined, or pressured. Core state functions\'97payments, personnel records, scientific data\'97were opened to an unelected private actor whose incentives were not those of a public servant.\
\
